    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence assessment reveals a deliberate and significant escalation in U.S. military posture across the Western Pacific, centered on the Valiant Shield 2026 and Resolute Dragon 26 joint exercises. Seven Nimitz-class carrier strike groups (CVN-73, CVN-70, CVN-68, CVN-76, CVN-74, CVN-71, CVN-72) are deployed in the Philippine Sea, Sea of Japan, and adjacent waters, conducting sustained joint operations with Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force assets. This represents the most concentrated carrier presence in the region in decades, signaling a clear deterrent posture against Chinese naval assertiveness in the South China Sea and Taiwan Strait. Amphibious ready groups (LHA-6, LHD-2, LHD-8, LPD-22, LPD-18, LPD-20) are strategically positioned to enable rapid amphibious assault and maritime security operations, while destroyers (DDG-108, DDG-56, DDG-65, DDG-86) and cruisers (CG-62, CG-59) provide layered air and missile defense, escort, and strike capabilities. The aircraft data corroborates this operational tempo, with USAF C-17, C-130J, and KC-135/KC-46 platforms conducting strategic and tactical airlift, aerial refueling, and ISR missions in direct support of the exercises. Notably, P-8 Poseidon maritime patrol aircraft are conducting sustained ASW and ISR operations, reflecting heightened focus on submarine threats and regional maritime domain awareness. The absence of forward-deployed submarines in the data may indicate a shift toward surface and air-centric operations or reporting gaps. The exercises serve as a critical platform for testing new asymmetric capabilities, including unmanned systems and attack drones, which are being transferred to Philippine forces to enhance their maritime domain awareness and deterrence. This multi-domain deployment—spanning carriers, amphibious ships, destroyers, cruisers, and a mix of transport, ISR, and training aircraft—demonstrates a deliberate U.S. strategy to project power, reinforce allied deterrence, and counter Chinese area-denial strategies. The operational tempo and geographic distribution suggest a long-term commitment to regional stability, with implications for both deterrence and crisis response in the Indo-Pacific.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
